            <div type="cave" xml:lang="en">
                <head type="cave">Cave <hi rend="bold">76</hi>
                </head>
                <div>
                    <head>Description</head>
                    <div>
                        <head>Overview</head>
                        <p>Cave <hi rend="bold">76</hi> is a fine example of a box-shaped cave of substandard size: height, width, and depth all measure about 2 m instead of 2.2 m (fig. <ptr target="map_cave_76_EN.svg"/>). Yet the engravings in this well-positioned and well-shaped cave are incomplete, as described above in the Introduction. The carvers set about engraving the seventh chapter of the <hi rend="italic">Golden Light Sutra</hi>, the first six chapters of which had already been engraved in cave <hi rend="bold">73</hi>. They began on wall d, but discontinued work after column 41.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div>
                        <head>Location</head>
                        <list>
                            <item>Southern slope, section E, more than 6 m above the walkway.</item>
                            <item>Direction of wall f: 338˚.</item>
                            <item>At a distance of about 3.4 m to the west, is the neighboring cave <hi rend="bold">75</hi>, whose floor is ca. 40 cm higher. 70 cm below the floor of cave <hi rend="bold">76</hi> is the ceiling of cave <hi rend="bold">77</hi>; and 85–90 cm below it is the ceiling of cave <hi rend="bold">74</hi>. </item>
                        </list>
                    </div>
                    <div>
                        <head>Shape</head>
                        <p>Box-shaped, with open front. Wall e is slightly concave. The ground plan is slightly trapezoidal in shape, with wall d considerably longer than wall f. The ceiling is horizontal.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div>
                        <head>Measurements</head>
                        <list>
                            <item>Wall d: height at the front 200 cm, at the rear 202 cm, width 208 cm.</item>
                            <item>Wall e: height at midpoint 208 cm, width 214 cm. </item>
                            <item>Wall f: height at the front 208 cm, at the rear 203 cm, width 160 cm (below) – 180 cm (above).</item>
                            <item>Width of entrance: 196 cm.</item>
                        </list>
                    </div>
                    <div>
                        <head>Changes</head>
                        <p>Two corresponding man-made holes near the entrance in walls d and f, ca. 164–168 cm above the floor, have a diameter of ca. 4 cm.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div xml:id="Site_WFY_Section_Ea_Cave76_d_en">
                    <head>Wall d</head>
                    <div>
                        <head>Layout</head>
                        <list>
                            <item>A polished area, 178 × 195 cm, begins 0–10 cm from the entrance and 10 cm from the ceiling; it ends 0–6 cm from the rear wall and 16–18 cm above the floor. </item>
                            <item>The field of script is a narrow vertical rectangle, 167 × 88 cm, at the front part of the wall. It begins 11.5 cm from the entrance and 33 cm below the ceiling, ending 22 cm above the floor, and 110 cm from the rear wall. <!--After column 15 no characters have been carved in an area beginning ca. 148 cm above the floor and reaching to the upper edge of the field of script. With/In column 41 engraving stopped altogether. Only vertical grid lines continue in eight columns for another 17 cm. Characters may once have been written here with a brush.--></item>
                        </list>
                    </div>
