                <div xml:id="Site_WFY_Section_Ea_Cave76_e_en">
                    <head>Wall e</head><!-- <head>Layout</head>-->
                    <p>Rough abrasion; no engravings.</p>
                </div>
                <div xml:id="Site_WFY_Section_Ea_Cave76_f_en">
                    <head>Wall f</head><!-- <head>Layout</head>-->
                    <p>A field that extends over the width of the entire wall, from 16 to 169 cm above the floor, has undergone some preparatory abrasion of the surface; but there was no polishing, and no engravings were made. </p>
                </div>
                <div xml:id="Site_WFY_Section_Ea_Cave76_discussion_en">
                    <head>Discussion</head>
                    <bibl>
                        <ref type="biblio" target="Pengjiasheng1988">7</ref>
                        <note>
                            <p>Peng gives the dimensions of the cave and calculates its volume at 8.628 cubic meters. He identifies the text carved on wall d as part of the <hi rend="italic">Perfection of Wisdom Sutra</hi> (<hi rend="italic">
                                    <foreign xml:lang="sa">Prajñāpāramitā-sūtra</foreign>
                                </hi>; <foreign xml:lang="zh">般若波羅蜜經</foreign>), without specifying further. He was given this information by Hu Wenhe.</p>
                        </note>
                    </bibl>
                    <bibl>
                        <ref type="biblio" target="Huwenhe1992">10</ref>
                        <note>
                            <p>Hu Wenhe gives the same dimensions of the cave as published in <ref type="biblio" target="Pengjiasheng1988"/>. He also repeats the identification of the text carved as part of the <hi rend="italic">Perfection of Wisdom Sutra</hi>.</p>
                        </note>
                    </bibl>
                    <bibl>
                        <ref type="biblio" target="HuWenhe1994">68</ref>
                        <note>
                            <p>Hu Wenhe repeats the information in his earlier publication, <ref type="biblio" target="Huwenhe1992"/>.</p>
                        </note>
                    </bibl>
                    <bibl>
                        <ref type="biblio" target="Li_Deng1997">44</ref>
                        <note>
                            <p>The authors give measurements of the cave and of wall d, on which they identify the <hi rend="italic">Perfection of Wisdom Sutra</hi>. They write that no texts were carved on walls e and f.</p>
                        </note>
                    </bibl>
                    <bibl>
                        <ref type="biblio" target="ChengduKaoguFaxian2008">389, 408</ref>
                        <note>
                            <p>The editors of the Chengdu Municipal Institute of Cultural Relics and Archaeology provide measurements and a description of the architecture of the cave. For the first time, they correctly identify the text, carved on wall d, as chapter 6 of the <hi rend="italic">Synoptic Golden Light Sutra</hi> (<foreign xml:lang="zh">合部金光明經</foreign>), with 32 columns still legible. They suggest that the beginning of the text has been lost to erosion and they point out that it was left unfinished.</p>
                        </note>
                    </bibl>
                    <bibl>
                        <ref type="biblio" target="LeeSonyaS2009">50, 52</ref>
                        <note>
                            <p>Lee includes cave <hi rend="bold">76</hi> in her cluster V, which corresponds to section E. She identifies the text as excerpts from the <hi rend="italic">Diamond Sutra</hi>.
                                
                                </p>
                        </note>
                    </bibl>
                    <bibl>
                        <ref type="biblio" target="Cao_Yu2009">13</ref>
                        <note>
                            <p>Cao and Yu provide measurements only for the wall and the surface area of wall d. They write that the sutra text is almost illegible due to severe erosion, saying that only 30 columns of 74 characters have survived, for a total of 2,220.</p>
                        </note>
                    </bibl>
                    <bibl>
                        <ref type="biblio" target="Qin_Zhang_Lei2015">100–101, 125, 434–437</ref>
                        <note>
                            <p>The authors repeat the information in <ref type="biblio" target="ChengduKaoguFaxian2008"/>. In addition, they provide a diagram of wall d and a transcription of the engraved text, which they analyze with their own detailed scheme.</p>
                        </note>
                    </bibl>
                    <bibl>
                        <ref type="biblio" target="HidaRomi_2015">110</ref>
                        <note>
                            <p>Hida writes that the final part of chapter 6 of the <hi rend="italic">Synoptic Golden Light Sutra</hi> was carved on wall d. No texts were carved on walls e and f.</p>
                        </note>
                    </bibl>
                    <bibl>
                        <ref type="biblio" target="Dengxingliang2016">79</ref>
                        <note>
                            <p>Deng Xingliang gives the measurements and a general description of the cave. He writes that a sutra is carved on wall d, while walls e and f are bare.</p>
                        </note>
                    </bibl>
                </div>
            </div>
